Boil a large #pot of salted water for the veg.

Chop the @baby potatoes{500%g} into 2cm chunks. Trim the @carrot{1} then chop into 1cm rounds (no need to peel).

Add the veg to the boiling water and cook until fork tender, ~{15-20%minutes}.

Once cooked, drain in a #colander and return to the #pot, off the heat.

Add a knob of @butter{knob} and a splash of @milk{to taste}(optional) or @water{to taste}. Mash with a #potato masher{} until smooth. Season with @salt{to taste} and @pepper{to taste}. Cover to keep warm.

== Tomato Salad ==

Chop the @tomato{1} into wedges.

Peel and grate the @garlic{1}(peeled and grated) (or use a #garlic press{}).

To make your dressing, mix the @balsamic vinegar{1%sachet} with @oil{1%tbsp}.

Just before serving toss the @salad leaves{40%g} and tomato through the dressing and season to taste with @salt{to taste} and @pepper{to taste}.

== Creamy Dijon Beef ==

Place a large pan over high heat with a drizzle of @oil{to taste}.

Once the pan is very hot, sear the @Irish beef strips{250%g} until cooked through, shifting as they colour, ~{2-3%minutes}.

> IMPORTANT: Wash hands and equipment after handling raw meat and its packaging. Meat is safe to eat when the outside is browned.

Remove the beef strips from the pan and cover to keep warm.

Return the pan to medium-high heat with a drizzle of @oil{to taste}.

Fry the garlic for ~{1%minute} then add the @creme fraiche{110%g}, @mustard{1/2%sachet}, and @beef stock{1%sachet}.

Cook, stirring until slightly thickened for ~{2-3%minutes}.

Once the sauce has thickened slightly, return the beef strips to the pan.

Toss to coat the beef strips well in the sauce.

Divide the mash between plates.

Top with the creamy Dijon beef.

Serve the tomato salad alongside.